Project 2 by Isabel Coupland¶

Introduction¶

Scientific question: What genetic changes in the auditory processing pathway of mammals allow for high-frequency hearing, leading to the convergent evolution of echolocation?¶

Echolocation is the location of objects using reflected sound. Three species of mammals that use echolocation are Eptesicus fuscus (Big brown bat), Hipposideros armiger (Great roundleaf bat), and Orcinus orca (Killer whale). Three mammals that cannot echolocate are Cynopterus sphinx (Greater short-nosed fruit bat), Pteropus vampyrus (Large flying fox), and Homo sapiens.

Some genes known to be involved with the auditory pathway and hearing loss include:

  • Prestin (SLC26A5; involved in cochlear hair cell motility and ion exchange, critical for hearing sensitivity),
  • GJB2 (associated with hearing loss in humans),
  • CDH23 (responsible for stereocilia organization and hair bundle formation),
  • PCDH15 (maintenance of normal retinal and cochlear function),
  • OTOF (vesicle membrane fusion, associated with deafness in mice), and
  • KCNQ4 (cochlear neuron excitability).

The data used in this project was sourced from NCBI Nucleotide and NCBI GEO:

  • NCBI Nucleotide https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore As stated on this databases website, "The Nucleotide database is a collection of sequences from several sources, including GenBank, RefSeq, TPA and PDB. Genome, gene and transcript sequence data provide the foundation for biomedical research and discovery."
  • NCBI GEO https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/ As stated on this website, "GEO is a public functional genomics data repository supporting MIAME-compliant data submissions. Array- and sequence-based data are accepted. Tools are provided to help users query and download experiments and curated gene expression profiles."
Scientific hypothesis: If there are similar changes in the sequences and expression of hearing-related genes in the brain of mammals, then an auditory processing pathway will evolve, allowing for the use of echolocation.¶

The coding sequences of each gene for all 6 species listed above were downloaded as a FASTA file from NCBI nucleotide. The sequences for each species was then compiled into one file for each gene and Multiple sequence alignment was performed using Clustalw2. A phylogenetic tree was created for the alignment of each gene.

  • Multiple sequence alignment allows me to compare the sequences of a gene for each species, then plot it using a phylogenetic tree to determine which gene(s) are most similar among echolocating species.

RNA-Seq gene expression data is from NCBI GEO, samples come from the brains of 5 echolocating and 3 non-echolocating species of bats. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE40993 The data for all 8 organisms was compiled into one file and read into the notebook. RNA-seq differential expression was explicitly calculated in the notebook as I could not get RNA-seq to actually run.

  • RNA-seq allows us to compare the gene expression data for each species, then plot the logF2C and p-value on a volcano plot to see which genes are most differentially expressed between echolocating and non-echolocating species.

Import/download packages¶

  • Bio: This a Biopython package that gives access to many tools you need for bioinformatics. The subpackages available allow you to do things such as multiple sequence alignments, BLAST searches, make phylogenetic trees, and more. You need to download Biopython first. To learn more about the Bio package and how to install Biopython see here: https://biopython.org/docs/1.75/api/Bio.html https://biopython.org/wiki/Download
    • Bio.Align.Applications: a subpackage of Bio that gives access to the alignment command line tool wrappers for programs such as MUSCLE, Clustalw, ClustalOmega, Prank, Mafft, Dialign2-2, PROBCONS, TCoffee, and MSAProbs. This gives a variety of options on how to perform multiple sequence alignment in python. In this project I use MafftCommandline to perform MSA on the prestin gene as an example. To learn more about the Bio.Align.Applications package see here: https://biopython.org/docs/1.76/api/Bio.Align.Applications.html
    • AlignIO: This subpackage allows you to input/output multiple sequence alignments as alignment objects. You could perform an alignment with this package but only if the sequences are already the same length. If they're different lengths, you should use the Bio.Align.Applications package or another program to perform the MSA first. You can then read in the alignment, parse it, write it to a file, or convert between file types using AlignIO. In this project I use AlignIO to read in alignments that were performed in my computer terminal. To learn more about the AlignIO package see here: https://biopython.org/docs/1.75/api/Bio.AlignIO.html
    • Phylo: This subpackage gives you everything you need to make phylogenetic trees. In this project, I use the Phylo package to read in trees that were made in clustalw2 outside of jupyter notebook. I also use Bio.Phylo.TreeConstruction which allows you to compute distances from an alignment then construct a tree off the calculations. This subpackage gives you the ability to make many different kinds of trees, including NJ, UPGMA, and parsimony. To learn more about about the Phylo package see here: https://biopython.org/docs/1.75/api/Bio.Phylo.html https://biopython.org/wiki/Phylo
  • IO: This module is Python's main way for dealing with various types of I/O (input/output). There are three main types of I/O (text I/O, binary I/O and raw I/O); a concrete object belonging to any of these types is called a file object (aka stream or file-like object). Each object can be read-only, write-only, or read-write and are specific about the type of data you give them. In this project I use StringIO which is part of Text I/O. Text I/O expect and return strings. To learn more about IO read here: https://docs.python.org/3/library/io.html
  • pandas: This package provides flexible data structures to make data analysis easy. It's built upon NumPy. The two main data structures of pandas are Series (1-D) and DataFrame (2-D). I use pandas DataFrame in this project to organize data. It makes it easy to add columns and rows for calculations. To learn more about pandas see here: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/getting_started/overview.html
  • NumPy: is a python library that contains multidimensional array and matrix data structures. It can be used to perform a variety of mathematical operations on arrays. In this project I use NumPy for calculating log2 fold change, for example. To learn more about NumPy, see here: https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/index.html#reference
  • bioinfokit: provides simple functionalities to analyze, visualize, and interpret biological data from genomics experiments. bioinfokit requires Python 3, NumPy, scikit-learn, seaborn, pandas, matplotlib, and SciPy. It can make many types of plots including volcano plot, Venn diagram, manhatten plot, and more. In this project I use bioinfokit to make volcano plots to show differential expression of genes. To learn more about bioinfokit, see here: https://pypi.org/project/bioinfokit/
  • SciPy: like NumPy, SciPy is a python library used to perform various operations. SciPy is for scientific and technical computing and contains modules for optimization, linear algebra, integration, interpolation, special functions, FFT, signal and image processing, ODE solvers and other tasks common in science and engineering. I use SciPy in this project for some of the calculations involved in RNAseq. To learn more about SciPy, see here: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/tutorial/index.html#user-guide
  • statsmodels.sandbox.stats.multicomp: This package is used to perform some of the statistics. It's used in this project for testing results and adjustment of p-value for multiple tests. To learn more see here: https://www.statsmodels.org/0.8.0/generated/statsmodels.sandbox.stats.multicomp.multipletests.html

Analysis 1: Multiple sequence alignment using ClustalW2/Phylogenetic trees¶

Multiple sequence alignment is the alignment of three or more biological sequences of similar lengths. ClustalW2 produces multiple sequence alignments of divergent sequences by calculating the best match for the selected sequences and lining them up so that the identities, similarities and differences can be seen. The file input used in this project is a FASTA file containing the sequences of a gene for each species, although multiple file types are accepted. The output is a CLUSTAL file that shows the alignments. It can also output a guide tree file (.dnd) and phylogenetic tree (.ph). Evolutionary relationships can be seen by viewing the phylogenetic tree. Species that are clustered closest together have the most similar sequences and are thought to be closest related.

Clustalw2 was downloaded (http://www.clustal.org/download/current/) and performed in the computer terminal, as it was designed for interactive use and doesn't perform as well in jupyter notebook (I was unable to download the files through Jupyter notebook).

  • First, open terminal and type clustalw2
  • From the list, select option (1) Sequence Input From Disc
  • Type in file name [prestin.txt]
  • Select option (2) Multiple Alignments
  • Next, select option (1) Do complete multiple alignment now Slow/Accurate
  • Type in name for CLUSTAL output file [prestin.aln], pairwise alignment will be performed and guide tree will be established.
  • Type in name for new guide tree [prestin.dnd]
  • Multiple sequence alignment will be performed based on guide tree and alignment file will be exported.
    • Based on guide tree, closest sequences are compared first, leaving the most unrelated sequence for comparison last.
  • Back at the main menu, select option (4) Phylogenetic trees
  • Next, select option (4) Draw tree now
  • Type in name for PHYLIP tree output file [prestin.ph]
  • Analysis is complete and you may leave program

Below is an example of how the main menu of clustalw2 looks like:

Multiple sequence alignment using mafft¶

Here is the multiple sequence alignment of prestin to show how it would look using mafft instead. I went with clustalw2 because I liked the way the phylogenetic tree looked better.

In [6]:
# define global variable in_file which represents the file containing sequence of prestin gene
in_file = "prestin.txt"
# use command line wrapper for mafft, input is the sequence, output is stdout (contains alignment) and stderr
mafft_cline = MafftCommandline(input=in_file)
# check if it worked
print(mafft_cline)

# define global variables stdout, stderr 
# assign output variables
stdout, stderr = mafft_cline()
# instead of saving output to file, parse the output with AlignIO directly
# use StringIO to turn string into handle
align = AlignIO.read(StringIO(stdout), "fasta")
print(align)

## make phylogenetic tree
# define global variable constructor -- DistanceTreeConstructor is a distance based tree constructor
constructor = DistanceTreeConstructor()
# define global variable calculator -- DistanceCalculator is distance matrix calculator for MSA
calculator = DistanceCalculator('identity')
# define global variable dm -- use calculator to calculate distances for alignment of prestin
dm = calculator.get_distance(align)
# define global variable njtree -- neighbor joining tree based off calculated distances
njtree = constructor.nj(dm)
# flip branches so deeper clades are displayed at top
njtree.ladderize()
# plot the tree
Phylo.draw(njtree)

Analysis 2: RNAseq - explicitly calculating differential gene expression/Volcano Plot¶

I could not get pyrpipe or DESeq2 to run so I have performed these calculations instead.

  • Calculate the FPKM by averaging over the experiments, and then normalizing the number of reads mapped to each gene (could not normalize based on gene length due to lack of data) and the total number of read mapped to protein-coding sequences in the alignment.

  • Once we have the FPKM in the pandas dataframe for the control (non-echolocating) versus echolocating experiments, then we can calculate the log2fold change and the p-value.

Volcano plot is a type of scatterplot that is commonly used to display the results of RNA-seq. It shows the p-value versus magnitude of change. This allows us to visualize which genes have large changes that are also statistically significant. We input the values from performing differential gene expression calculations. The dots that are outermost and towards the top are likely to be the most biologically significant genes.

# parse the counts dataframe just for the control (non-echolocating) experiments
# define global variable control_exp -- contains the names of each species that are non-echolocating
control_exp = list(metadata.loc[metadata['condition'] == 'control'].index)
print(control_exp)

# parse the counts dataframe just for the echolocating experiments
# define global variable echolocating_exp -- contains the names of each species that are echolocating
echolocating_exp = list(metadata.loc[metadata['condition'] == 'echolocating'].index)
print(echolocating_exp)

## Add a column to the counts dataframe that has the total sum of reads for each gene depending on condition
# Sum control column
counts['Sum control'] = counts[control_exp].sum(axis=1)
# Sum echolocating column
counts['Sum echolocating'] = counts[echolocating_exp].sum(axis=1)
#print(counts.head()) # uncomment for code check

## Calculate the mean and standard deviation to use later when calculating the p-value, add columns to controls df
# Mean number of reads for controls
counts['Mean control'] = counts[control_exp].mean(axis=1)
# Mean number of reads for echolocating 
counts['Mean echolocating'] = counts[echolocating_exp].mean(axis=1)
# Standard deviation of reads for control
counts['STD controls'] = counts[control_exp].std(axis=1)
# Standard deviation of reads for echolocating
counts['STD echolocating'] = counts[echolocating_exp].std(axis=1)

Note: gene length is excluded from calculations below due to the data not being available from NCBI GEO. I also tried to use Biomart to get the gene lengths but the code and online version weren't working successfully.

Analysis of Results¶

The results of the multiple sequence alignments and phylogenetic trees show that prestin is the only gene where echolocating species are all clustered together. Close clustering shows that the sequences are more similar. It does not rule out the importance of the other genes but it shows that prestin likely has a more important role in echolocation.

The results of the differential gene expression analysis and volcano plot show that none of the genes I performed MSA on were significantly differentially expressed. This is likely because the data comes from brain samples, not inner ear samples (which is where prestin is expressed). However, the top genes here that are differentially expressed could be explored more as to their roles in echolocation. Two of the top up-regulated genes, ENSMLUG00000029089 which codes for ribosomal protein 16 and ENSMLUG00000015026 which codes for KLHDC3, when put through reactome shows they both have roles in cellular responses to stimuli.

In this project I have identified that prestin has a similar sequence among echolocating mammals. While I was unable to confirm the differential expression of prestin (due to sample data being from the brain and not the inner ear), I have identified two proteins that are significantly differentially expressed and could have a role in echolocation. Thus, my hypothesis was correct that echolocating species have similarities in gene sequences and gene expression leading to an altered auditory processing pathway.
